Gotta love the TaxMan… 🔥🦈🔥 @hubermanlab DOPAMINE, SURPRISE & “THE ONE THAT GOT AWAY”•
-
Being in pursuit of something and especially, being right on the cusp of obtaining a reward  is a very strong stimulus for dopamine release in the brain. But perhaps the greatest stimulus of all for dopamine release is when that is followed by positive surprise. 
-
The name for it is “reward prediction error”. When we anticipate a reward, and it is not obtained or is smaller than what we expected, our baseline level of dopamine drops below what it was prior to the entire pursuit. Eventually returns to normal. But we learn something about the value of the pursuit that preceded that lower reward.
-
This video was shot during my lab’s an expedition with @michaelmuller7 to collect footage of great white sharks for a fear/anxiety VR stimulus @stanfordmed 
-
We wanted tuna for our dinner and we had one on the line… we were expecting a (meal) reward. A local great white reminded us that, when they are around, humans eat last. However, the reward of seeing it breach was greater than the meal we would’ve had.
-
I’ll also never forget that incident because when we get a big and unexpected release of dopamine, also leaves and indelible mark on our memory. 
-
You can start to see why dopamine is so fundamental to the evolution of every species. It’s the chemical currency that tells us about the value of our experiences and efforts.
-
The new episode of the Huberman Lab podcast out right now is all about dopamine, “reward prediction error” and the many important roles dopamine plays motivation, drive and sense of reward. It also covers how to overcome procrastination by leveraging dopamine dynamics.
-
You can find the episode in all formats by going to hubermanlab.com Everything is timestamped so you can navigate quickly to the topics most of interest to you.

Predators & Protein > If you choose to actively engage in high-risk activities, you better be prepared to “Stop the Bleed” > It’s literally a matter of life & death and why I never dive or travel without a CAT tourniquet…
🩸🦈🩸 #abc4explore / repost ➡️ @northamericanrescue @kevin._.blanco was #spearfishing off of Marathon Key, Florida when a large bull shark attacked him as he struggled with an entangled fish at 70 feet! The shock of the bite caused Kevin to scream underwater costing him precious air from his lungs. Thankfully his two diving partners were able to help him swim back to the surface and get back on the boat. Blood from a severed vein and other vessels was squirting all over the swim step and outboard engine. Remembering a conversation he had just had with his father @omarblancofl, a career firefighter/paramedic, about tourniquets, Kevin and his friends improvised a TQ out of their wide, rubber weight belts and were able to stop the bleeding (great makeshift option- the wider the TQ the lower the pressure needed to stop bleeding - 2 weight belts = 6 inch+ TQ width). After a 20 minute boat ride, they got back to land and were met by Marathon EMS who converted the TQ to a CAT and onboarded TXA. Due to their rapid efforts to control bleeding, Kevin did not require any blood transfusions at the hospital but he did receive over 150 stitches. We wish him a continued rapid and complete recovery and are glad he listened to his dad’s advice about the importance of having an emergency plan and TQs! #beprepared #sharkattack #stopthebleed #bethedifference

Wise words from @JuanSharks… It’s understandable that the thought of a shark attack can be terrifying.
However, the solution to this problem is not to kill sharks out of fear. We need to take a step back and understand our impact on the ocean, educate ourselves on how to safely coexist with these creatures, and adapt our behavior accordingly.
Firstly, we need to acknowledge that humans have a major impact on the ocean and its inhabitants. From pollution to overfishing, our actions have consequences that ripple throughout the ecosystem. By understanding our impact and taking steps to reduce it, we can create a healthier environment for all creatures, including sharks.
Secondly, education is key. We need to learn more about sharks and how to safely interact with them. This means being more cautious when entering the ocean, wearing proper gear like a mask and fins, and being aware of our surroundings. It also means not acting like a hurt or injured animal by splashing around with our heads out of the water. Sharks are attracted to splashing and erratic movements, so it’s important to remain calm and avoid behavior that could be mistaken for prey. Finally, we need to treat the ocean like a wild place. Just as you wouldn’t run around like a hurt zebra in the African savanna, we need to approach the ocean with respect and caution.
We must remember that we are entering the sharks’ habitat, not the other way around. By adapting our behavior and treating the ocean as awild place, we can coexist with sharks and other marine life in a safe and sustainable way. (see @juansharks IG feed for full post) #juansharks

While sharks have a bad reputation & people demonize them, this video is just more proof that we’re not on their menu & they really don’t want anything to do with us. This shark could’ve easily killed someone if it wanted to.

A moment i’ll never forget! 🔨🦈

Polite predator & prey interactions captured by @sharynhodges - l am lost for words. 

I honestly thought I was going to witness a shark attack. I was shaking whilst taking footage and screaming (for what I have no idea).

My battery was about 8 minutes left and well if you have a drone you know that’s more like five minutes. I saw some dolphins swimming rather quickly so I thought I would get some slow mo action and I could see they were heading to another small pod so I thought let me fly a bit higher and get the two pods joining. 

Little did I know there was a HUGE great white in the middle as they circled him and dived under and over him.

I had a decision to make, bring the drone home for a battery change or stay for another five minutes. I came home in a stress and flew out again.

At this stage my heart was pounding and I was so stressed. How do I let the surfers know that there a shark approaching. I just stayed with them and told my myself whatever happens. Happens. Obviously believing that the shark will do what I always thought it would, be curious and turn. And knowing that the dolphins were there as back up. I really believed that this was something incredibly special that I was witnessing.

Moment of truth. The shark approached the surfers, my controller was shaking in my hands. I was freaking out!!!!!!

But the shark just casually went up to the surfer and turned away, but it looked like he was turning back towards the surfer, but a couple of dolphins made sure he was headed another direction.

I am blown away by nature. Every single day I learn something new. Always surprising me.

Mako shark collects its unusual prize, a california sea lion.

Since these sharks were gifted with the uncanny ability to run down even the fastest prey, makos don’t usually hunt sea lions. However, this drone footage is proof that they will switch it up and adapt to what’s available when they need to.

Mako sharks are among the ocean’s fastest swimmers, reaching speeds of up to 45 mph. Their streamlined bodies are optimized for agility and speed, traits that serve them well when hunting their preferred prey of fast-swimming fish like tuna and mackerel.

Yet despite their formidable capabilities, makos face their own set of challenges. Overfishing poses a significant threat, as does the ongoing degradation of marine ecosystems, affecting both their hunting grounds and the availability of their preferred food sources.

As ocean conditions continue to evolve and become increasingly unpredictable, the ability of all marine species to adapt will be put to the test. If there’s any certainty in life, it’s that natural systems will always find a way to persevere, even in the most challenging of times.

Who’s below the surface? It’s Yvon Chouinard!

We were delighted to see Yvon at the Farallones on Tuesday. We had a feeling it was him because of his distinctive age spots, blocky head, and size but needed to confirm the dorsal fin before sharing. 

Yvon was named after Patagonia’s founder Yvon Chouinard in honor of his demonstrated commitment to our environment. We first saw Yvon, the shark, in 2021. It is surprising to have first seen him so recently, as he is well over 75 years old. 

Yvon is an impressive 17 feet in length and was  significantly ‘rotund’ on Tuesday. He did not make an appearance in our 2022 research season so we are glad to see he is alive and doing well in 2023. White sharks like Yvon are unprotected beyond our exclusive economic zone and continue to face threats such as poaching, orcas, and high seas fisheries. 

Yvon’s age and size provides invaluable insight into white shark metrics like growth rate which in turn can reflect the health of our ecosystem. Without our research, key members of the trophic food chain like Yvon could decline and scientists and stakeholders (you) would be unaware.

We need YOUR support to continue researching sharks like Yvon. Please donate through the link in bio, everything goes directly to white shark research.

So what? They are perfect aliens!   Hammerheads are such a crazy example of evolution - just look at their heads! Their wide, flat head (called a cephalofoil) has an increased surface area for more ampullae of lorenzini, which are the jelly filled pores that detect electrical signals in the water. They can scan the sea floor and detect their favourite food source, stingrays, and use that flat face of theirs to help pin their prey down.

Their eyes are set on either end of the cephalofoil, giving them nearly a nearly 360 degree range of vision… meaning they absolutely know when photographers like me are obsessively hanging around trying to get a great shot. I guess Gaia picked up on all my good vibes and decided to swim over to get her picture taken 😉
